The Duration Mismatch
One of the fun things about crises is that we all get to learn new stuff.=
=C2=A0
This time around, the once-blissfully-banking-unaware are now familiar with=
 acronyms like SVB, FDIC, SIPC, and GSIB. A mere ten days ago, we thought U=
S Treasuries were boring and risk-free; now, we understand that that is onl=
y true if you=E2=80=99re fortunate enough to be in a position to hold them =
until maturity. Not all banks can, it turns out, because as we now know, ba=
nks =E2=80=9Cborrow short and lend long.=E2=80=9D I see you nodding smugly.=
 You recognize that problem now. That=E2=80=99s our favorite new term of th=
is fresh crisis: a duration mismatch.=C2=A0
Plenty of experts, and plenty of non-experts, have written about duration m=
ismatches over the past ten days, so I won=E2=80=99t bore you. What you nee=
d to know, as if you don=E2=80=99t already, is that depositors can pull the=
ir money whenever they feel like it, but banks that bought long-dated Treas=
uries in a rising rate environment have to hold them for years or suffer lo=
sses. And when depositors hit their ever-present option to withdraw right n=
ow, banks have no choice but to sell right now, and the duration mismatch r=
ears its ugly, now-familiar head.
I think that the main reason people are unhappy with the tech industry righ=
t now is another sort of duration mismatch: tech experiments short to innov=
ate long.=C2=A0
There are all of the other very real issues people have discussed ad nauseu=
m =E2=80=93 the money, the tweets, the clubbiness and lack of diversity, th=
e grandiose visions =E2=80=93 but as that old Tiger Woods Nike campaign poi=
nts out:=C2=A0
If people felt that tech really were improving their lives, they=E2=80=99d =
forgive the industry a little excess and hubris. And the process of improvi=
ng lives through technology is a winding one.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99ve written about this, too, in different terms, in The Invisible =
Hand=E2=80=99s Visible Swarm:=C2=A0
As Sebastian Mallaby put it more succinctly in The Power Law: =E2=80=9CThe =
future can be discovered by means of iterative, venture-backed experiments.=
 It cannot be predicted.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The implication is that at any given present moment, the things that the te=
ch industry is funding and building seem unimpactful or silly or doomed-to-=
fail or unlikely to increase the potential for human happiness. Then, like =
a speedrun of natural selection, the strong survive, the losers die, and if=
 we=E2=80=99re lucky, the useful mutations they=E2=80=99ve unearthed are pi=
cked up by the next generation, and the next generation uses them to build =
products that increase the potential for human happiness.=C2=A0
Very few people want to view their life=E2=80=99s work as an experiment, th=
ough, so each individual actor in the system tries to convince themselves, =
investors, employees, customers, and the general public that their thing is=
 the important thing, the end, not the means to an end. In the short-term, =
there=E2=80=99s a lot of bluster about how this consumer app or B2B softwar=
e product is going to change the world, and when it doesn=E2=80=99t, it=E2=
=80=99s held up as yet another example of the tech industry=E2=80=99s mispl=
aced hubris.=C2=A0
Of course, some things do succeed. But by the time they=E2=80=99ve reached =
enough scale to make a meaningful dent on the potential for human happiness=
, those humans don=E2=80=99t get much happiness out of them. Technological =
progress is an infinite hedonic treadmill.=C2=A0
Once we get used to the internet, we take it for granted. Once we=E2=80=99v=
e had all of the world=E2=80=99s music in our pockets for a couple days, we=
 complain about Spotify=E2=80=99s new UX or how buggy video podcasts can be=
=2E Once enough people have not died from=
 taking Moderna=E2=80=99s vaccine, w=
e spend time arguing over whether the vaccine is actually killing us.=C2=A0
Herein lies another rub. We=E2=80=99re terrible at counterfactuals, at =E2=
=80=9Crelating to or expressing what has not happened or is not the case.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
You take your mother to get the vaccine, she=E2=80=99s in and out in 15 min=
utes, and goes back to living her life. She doesn=E2=80=99t die, and of cou=
rse she doesn=E2=80=99t die =E2=80=93 she=E2=80=99s spent the last 70 years=
 living, and most people didn=E2=80=99t die from COVID, so your priors woul=
d suggest that she would have just gone on living. Sure, it=E2=80=99s nice =
that she can go out to dinner again without wearing a mask or worrying when=
 someone at the next table over coughs, but the appreciation fades quickly.=
 Going to dinner without worry is something we=E2=80=99ve always done, exce=
pt for a weird year or two, and naturally, it=E2=80=99s something that of c=
ourse we were going to do again. And thank god we don=E2=80=99t have to use=
 DoorDash or Instacart all the time anymore, or get on yet another Zoom or =
run through the same old streaming catalog on Netflix and HBO Max and and a=
nd, or or or.=C2=A0
Sometimes, I think the most self-serving thing the tech industry could prod=
uce is a fully immersive virtual reality experience coupled with an omnipot=
ent AI simulation engine that lets people replay versions of history withou=
t certain technologies. Call it Memento Mori, or, less catchily, Memento Tu=
 Mortuus Es.
There=E2=80=99s no Haber-Bosch process, Malthus was right, and you=E2=80=99=
re so hungry.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s no vaccine, and your mother is in the hospital, and you=E2=
=80=99re stuck outside because they won=E2=80=99t let you in for fear of co=
ntagion.=C2=A0
Less morbidly, there=E2=80=99s no Google Maps and you=E2=80=99re lost. Ther=
e=E2=80=99s no internet and you=E2=80=99re bored. There=E2=80=99s no little=
 experiment that seemed useless at the time but generated that one key insi=
ght that the next company used to build the thing that you use so often you=
 kinda forget it even exists.
But we don=E2=80=99t have such a device (yet) and we do very much have all =
of the things in our day-to-day lives that make us angry and frustrated and=
